03940nam a22006135i 9780292754904DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211998txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927549047 a10.7560/7772792doi  a(DE-B1597)588202  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aS604.4b.S546 1998 7aHIS0520002bisacsh04a630/.972/621 aSiemens, Alfred H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Favored Place :bSan Juan River Wetlands, Central Veracruz, A.D. 500 to the Present /cAlfred H. Siemens. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tList of Figures -- tPortrait -- tPreface: An Amiable Collaboration -- t1. Finding and Deciphering Patterned Ground in the Lowlands of Mesoamerica -- t2. Deducing the San Juan Basin in A.D. 500 -- t3. Probing the Ethnohistorical Literature Surrounding the Encounter -- t4. Reformatting Sixteenth-Century Documents -- t5. Maximizing Some Late-Eighteenth-Century Observations -- t6. Appreciating a Naturalist's Rendition of Central Veracruz in the Nineteenth Century -- t7. Struggling with a Technocratic Pathology of the Basin in Mid-Twentieth Century -- t8. Summing Up the Yields -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe wetlands of the San Juan Basin in Central Veracruz, Mexico, have been a favored place since the fifth century A.D., when Prehispanic people built an extensive network of canals and raised fields that allowed for almost year-round agriculture. Alfred Siemens' discovery of the remains of this network in the 1970s led him to uncover fifteen centuries of land-use history in the region. This book contains a full record of his findings. Siemens organizes his history of the San Juan Basin around the question: What relationships exist between Prehispanic agriculture and the production systems of the tropical lowlands in our own time? This focus allows him to chart the changes in human perceptions and uses of the landscape, from the Prehispanic wetland agricultural system to the drained pastures of today's cattle ranches. Amplified with air oblique photography, maps, and tables, and enriched with data from archaeology and colonial archives, this is an authoritative historical geography of a wetland landscape. Or, in the author's more modest words, "It seems to me that what I have here is a biography of a swamp."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aTraditional farmingzMexicozSan Juan River Region (Veracruz-Llave)xHistory. 0aWetland agriculturezMexicozSan Juan River Region (Veracruz-Llave)xHistory. 7aHISTORY / Historical Geography.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292754904423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292754904/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK